"Abstract After taking an inordinate amount of time to decide the issues, the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals ruled, on Monday 12 February 2001, that Napster infringed the copyrights of the record company and music publisher plaintiffs. However, the court sent the case back to the trial judge for the entry of a more narrowly drawn injunction. While the opinion is long and very tightly written (the Ninth Circuit does not want to be overturned by the US Supreme Court like it was in the infamous Betamax decision years earlier), it is an important short-term victory for the record industry, and provides an important impetus to Napster and other online music providers to create a new business model where users pay for the music they want. Whether Internet users are willing to pay ANYTHING for music, however, is still an open question."
